did.abstract: The GW Hatchet began in 1904, before that it was called the Weekly Columbian, before that the Columbian Call. The newspaper celebrated its 100th anniversary in 2004. Materials in this collection include a master set of microfilm of the student newspaper "Hatchet" from 1904 to 1989, photographs of Burton Sapin, Quigley's Pharmacy, Lloyd Elliott, Dr. Dennis O'leary, President and Nancy Reagan and other photos from the 1970 to 1980s.

bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The GW Hatchet began in 1904, before that it was called the Weekly Columbian before that the Columbian Call. The newspaper celebrated its 100th anniversary in 2004.

When the idea for a campus newspaper surfaced in 1902, the university was not yet named for the first president, but was still called Columbian University. It was not yet located in Foggy Bottom, but instead occupied a few nondescript buildings at 15th and H Streets, N.W. The student body was not especially united by any great amount of college spirit. But Charles W. Needham, Columbian University's dynamic President, was a visionary with dreams of a new and greater University, and a campus newspaper was a step in the right direction. Realizing that the University needed a publication that would create new student interest and spirit, Jesse W. Barrett, a law student and the son of a Missouri country editor, suggested to President Needham that a university newspaper be founded. With Dr. Needham's encouragement, Barrett formed a partnership with Otho L. Ferris, a fellow law student from Iowa. Mr. Ferris became the publication's business manager, and "The Weekly Columbian" was launched. Two years later, the University's name was changed to The George Washington University and the newspaper took the name, The University Hatchet. The first issue of the "Hatchet" appeared on October 5, 1904, with the editors noting that the present time was a critical period in the life of the University: GW was endeavoring to plant itself in the front rank of educational institutions.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Materials in this collection include a master set of microfilm of the student newspaper "Hatchet" from 1904 to 1989, photographs of Burton Sapin, Quigley's Pharmacy, Lloyd Elliott, Dr. Dennis O'leary, President and Nancy Reagan and other photos from the 1970 to 1980s. Also included are unbound and bound copies of the 1904-2005 Hatchet, campus posters, 1992-1997, intercollegiate newspaper association, football team entering the Tin Tabernacle in 1939, extra copies of the Hatchet, multiple photographs and negatives from their files. The materials range in date from 1904 to 2008.
Formerly RG#22.2

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into eight series: Office files, Images, Newspapers, Newspapers and posters, Images and awards, Newspapers, Newspapers, and Images.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains correspondence, brochures, forms, press releases, invitations, programs, media kits, memorandums, flyers, business card, constitution, and a magnet. Also included are copies of "The GW Hatchet Alumni News" and a published scrapbook of the class of 1995. They range in date from 1905 to 2005. The materials concern subscriptions, solicitation of advertisements (paper and online), employment, scholarships, suspension of the charter, special issues, the Board of Editors, unpublished "Hatchet" letter to the editor, history, history, Professor Charles Puffenbarger, Jesse W. Barrett, and the James Haley controversy.
Formerly vertical files

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs and negatives. These images cover the dates 1970 ca.- 1980 ca. Subjects include Burton Sapin, Quigley's Pharmacy, Lloyd Elliott, Dr. Dennis O'Leary, President Reagan and Nancy Reagan, Foggy Bottom Metro construction, Red Lion Row, Dick Gregory, various basketball players, the university yard and other campus scenes. The original numbering of the folders has been maintained.
Formerly ACC#490; original folder numbers maintained

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: This series contains photographs and negatives. These images cover the dates 1970s-80s. The images are from the files of the GW Hatchet. Subjects of these images include sports including basketball tennis, wrestling, crew, gymnastics, women's sports, golf, baseball, soccer, the hospital, the medical school, campus scenes, buildings including the Academic Center, Marvin Center, Lenthall Houses, Quigley's, dormitories including Thurston Hall, parking lots, individuals such as Jimmy Carter and Ronald Reagan), faculty senate, speakers, commencement, Martha's Marathon, concerts, theater, dances, elections, campus protests, rallies, Gelman Library groundbreaking and donors and Friends of the Libraries, and Aladin).
Formerly ACC#234
This series is unprocessed, please ask staff for assistance
